### Part 2: Pathloss Calculation

**Given:** $h_t = 0.05$ m, $h_r = 2.5$ m, assume $d = 100$ m

Using the **two-ray ground reflection model**:

$$L_{dB} = 40\log_{10}(d) - 20\log_{10}(h_t \cdot h_r)$$

<div class="math-left">

$$\begin{aligned}
L_{dB} &= 40\log_{10}(100) - 20\log_{10}(0.05 \times 2.5) \\
&= 40 \times 2 - 20\log_{10}(0.125) \\
&= 80 - 20 \times (-0.903) \\
&= 80 + 18.06 \\
&= 98.06 \text{ dB}
\end{aligned}$$

</div>

> **Pathloss: $L_{dB} = 98.06$ dB**

---

### Part 3: $E_b/N_0$ Calculation

**Step 1: Calculate Data Rate ($R_b$)**

$$R_b = 8 \text{ kbits/sample} \times 1500 \text{ samples/sec} = 12 \text{ Mbps}$$

**Step 2: Calculate Received Power ($P_r$)**

Assuming transmit power $P_t = 100$ mW (20 dBm, typical WiFi):

<div class="math-left">

$$\begin{aligned}
P_r &= P_t - L_{dB} \\
&= 20 - 98.06 \\
&= -78.06 \text{ dBm} \\
&= -108.06 \text{ dBW}
\end{aligned}$$

</div>

**Step 3: Calculate $E_b/N_0$ (shortcut formula)**

$$\frac{E_b}{N_0} (dB) = P_r (dBW) - 10\log_{10}(R_b) - 10\log_{10}(k) - 10\log_{10}(T)$$

<div class="math-left">

$$\begin{aligned}
\frac{E_b}{N_0} &= -108.06 - 10\log_{10}(12 \times 10^6) - 10\log_{10}(1.38 \times 10^{-23}) - 10\log_{10}(300) \\
&= -108.06 - 70.79 + 228.6 - 24.77 \\
&= 24.98 \text{ dB}
\end{aligned}$$

</div>

> **$E_b/N_0 = 24.98$ dB**
